"""
MKT Context Commentary — Hebrews chapters 10–11 (gap-fill pass)
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-hebrews-10-11-gaps.py

Key decisions:
- ch10: Yom Kippur annual-cycle logic; prophetic critique of externalized sacrifice; Mishnah Yoma
- ch10:32-39 community's prior persecution; enlightenment as baptismal term; Hab 2:4 in Qumran
- ch11: Enoch literature (1 Enoch); Aqedah traditions and zekhut avot; patriarchal tent-city contrast
- ch11:35 Maccabean martyrs from 2 Macc 6-7 and 4 Macc; resurrection-hope-under-torture
- ch11:37 sawn asunder = Isaiah tradition (Martyrdom of Isaiah); Maccabean warriors
- ch11:39-40 corporate eschatology: OT saints perfected together with NT community
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / "data" / "commentary" / source / f"{book}.json"
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f"  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}")

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

HEBREWS = json.loads(r"""
{
  "10": {
    "2": "<p>The rhetorical question \"would they not have stopped being offered?\" draws on the logic that the worshippers' continued consciousness of sin after each Yom Kippur proved the ritual's incompleteness. The Mishnah tractate Yoma describes the extensive emotional weight of the Day of Atonement — the community's fasting, lamentation, and prostration reflected a genuine annual reckoning with sin. The high priest's confessional prayer (vidui) over each sacrifice was a formal acknowledgment that the guilt remained real. The fact that the calendar required the same prayer, the same ritual, and the same community gathering year after year was evidence, Hebrews argues, of the system's own implicit acknowledgment that the prior year's sacrifice had not permanently resolved the problem.</p>",
    "3": "<p>\"In those sacrifices there is an annual reminder of sins\" identifies the Day of Atonement as a liturgical memorial of sin rather than a resolution of it. The concept of <em>anamnēsis</em> (active remembrance, memorial-recalling) in Jewish liturgy was multidimensional: the Passover Seder kept alive the memory of the Exodus; the Yom Kippur liturgy kept alive the memory of sin. The Mishnah records the high priest's public confession specifying \"sins, iniquities, and transgressions\" — an annual liturgical acknowledgment of the community's ongoing moral deficit before God. Hebrews reads this annual reminder as an implicit admission: a system that must annually remind worshippers of sin has not resolved the sin-problem but only managed it cyclically.</p>",
    "4": "<p>\"It is impossible for the blood of bulls and goats to take away sins\" was a claim that had antecedents in the prophetic tradition. Psalm 51:16-17 (\"You do not delight in sacrifice... The sacrifices of God are a broken spirit\") and Micah 6:6-8 (\"Does the LORD delight in thousands of rams?... He has shown you, O mortal, what is good\") reflected prophetic unease with purely external sacrifice. Isaiah 1:11-15 has God expressing weariness with the multiplicity of offerings when justice was absent. Within the sacrificial theology itself, Leviticus 17:11 grounded atonement in the life (blood) belonging to God — but the life of an animal was categorically insufficient to address human moral guilt. Hebrews gives explicit theological form to what the prophets had approached obliquely.</p>",
    "6": "<p>\"In burnt offerings and offerings for sin you took no pleasure\" (Ps 40:6) belongs to the biblical prophetic tradition of divine dissatisfaction with externalized sacrifice divorced from obedience. Hosea 6:6 (\"I desire mercy, not sacrifice\") was quoted by Jesus twice (Matt 9:13; 12:7) as a hermeneutical key. Amos 5:21-24 has God \"hating\" and \"despising\" the religious festivals when justice is absent. Samuel's statement to Saul (1 Sam 15:22: \"Obedience is better than sacrifice\") established the principle. Hebrews reads Psalm 40's placement of obedience over sacrifice not as a temporary prophetic protest but as the permanent divine evaluation: the sacrificial system was always subordinate to the will-doing that it symbolized.</p>",
    "7": "<p>\"I have come to do your will, O God, as it is written about me in the scroll of the book\" introduces the concept of the Son's mission as pre-scripted in Scripture. The phrase \"in the scroll of the book\" was understood by early Christians as the Torah's entire testimony about the Messiah — John 5:39 (\"These are the Scriptures that testify about me\") and Luke 24:27 (\"Beginning with Moses and all the Prophets, he explained what was said in all the Scriptures concerning himself\") reflect the same conviction. The Qumran community similarly understood their Teacher of Righteousness as the figure about whom the prophetic texts had spoken; early Christian exegesis applied the same hermeneutical conviction to Jesus.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The bracketing of the Levitical sacrifice categories — \"sacrifices and offerings and burnt offerings and sin offerings\" (drawing on LXX terminology for the four main types: <em>thysiai</em>, <em>prosphoras</em>, <em>holokautōmata</em>, <em>peri hamartias</em>) — covers the entire spectrum of the Mosaic sacrificial system. Leviticus 1-7 describes each category: whole burnt offerings (<em>olah</em>), grain offerings (<em>minhah</em>), peace offerings (<em>shelamim</em>), sin offerings (<em>chatat</em>), and guilt offerings (<em>asham</em>). Hebrews' comprehensive reference to all four categories (collapsing the full taxonomy into a list) signals that its argument is not about reforming one type of sacrifice but about the system as a whole — \"all of which are offered according to the law\" acknowledges their Mosaic legitimacy while arguing their provisionality.</p>",
    "9": "<p>\"He removes the first to establish the second\" uses the language of legal supersession familiar in the world of ancient near eastern treaties and Roman law. The replacement of a covenant by a subsequent covenant was a recognized legal category: suzerain-vassal treaties were renewed, modified, or superseded by subsequent agreements. The Mosaic covenant's supersession by the new covenant was anticipated within the OT itself (Jer 31:31-34: \"not like the covenant I made with their ancestors\"). The Qumran community had already enacted a version of this supersession by treating their community covenant as the new covenant that replaced the corrupted Jerusalem cult. Hebrews' \"removal of the first to establish the second\" is therefore a claim within a recognized theological-legal framework, not a novel invention.</p>",
    "10": "<p>\"We have been sanctified through the offering of the body of Jesus Christ once for all\" applies the language of priestly consecration to the entire community. In the Levitical system, sanctification (<em>hagiasmos</em>, from <em>qadash</em>) was a category applied to places (the tabernacle, the altar), times (the Sabbath, holy days), objects (the vessels of the sanctuary), and persons (the priests through ordination). The laity were sanctified through purification rituals before participating in major religious events but did not hold a permanently consecrated status. Hebrews claims that the community has received through Christ's offering the permanent sanctified status previously associated only with the Temple's holiest personnel and objects.</p>",
    "11": "<p>\"Every priest stands day after day\" contrasts the posture of the Levitical priests with the seated Son. The Mishnah records that there were no chairs in the Temple sanctuary — the priests performed their service standing. The physical standing was not merely practical but symbolic of ongoing service that was never finished. Josephus (Against Apion 2.106-107) describes the constant, day-and-night service of the Temple personnel. The rabbis later developed the principle that the standing of the priests represented their readiness for service (b. Sotah 38a). Against this picture of constant priestly standing, Hebrews presents the Son's seated posture (10:12; Ps 110:1) as the theological counterpoint: the work is done.</p>",
    "12": "<p>\"Having offered one sacrifice for sins for all time, sat down at the right hand of God\" echoes and fulfills Psalm 110:1 (\"Sit at my right hand\") within the specific context of completed priestly work. The Day of Atonement high priest did not sit during the ritual — the elaborate sequence of sacrifice, blood-sprinkling, and prayer required constant standing and movement. The Mishnah (Yoma 3:4-5:7) describes the high priest performing each stage of the ritual while standing or kneeling, never seated. When Hebrews describes the Son as seated after his offering, it invokes the contrast of the priest who has completed what no Levitical priest could complete — the once-for-all sacrifice that requires no repetition and therefore permits the priest to rest.</p>",
    "13": "<p>\"Waiting until his enemies are made a footstool for his feet\" (Ps 110:1b) reflects ANE royal victory iconography. Ancient Near Eastern imagery commonly depicted conquered kings prostrate or with the victor's foot on their neck (Josh 10:24; Ps 110:1). Egyptian pharaohs commissioned footstools depicting enemies; Mesopotamian royal reliefs showed defeated kings beneath the victorious ruler's feet. In Jewish eschatology, the nations' subjugation to YHWH and his Messiah was a standard element of the messianic age (Ps 2:9; Zech 12:3; 14:2-4). The \"waiting\" posture of the already-seated Son is the current phase of the messianic program: the decisive battle has been won (at the cross and resurrection), but the full public acknowledgment of that victory awaits the parousia.</p>",
    "14": "<p>\"By a single offering he has brought to completion for all time those who are being made holy\" addresses the tension between the completed offering (once for all) and the ongoing process of sanctification (those being made holy — present participle). The Yom Kippur ritual provided annual atonement that \"covered\" (kipper) sin without permanently eliminating it; the worshipper left the ceremony in a covered state that was not a permanent condition. Hebrews claims a different structure: the completion (teleiōsis, reaching the telos) achieved by the one offering is permanent and sufficient, while the community's ongoing sanctification is the present application of that completed event — not a supplement to an incomplete work but the unfolding consequence of a finished one.</p>",
    "15": "<p>\"The Holy Spirit also bears witness to us concerning this\" introduces the idea of Scripture's ongoing address — the Scriptures are not merely historical documents but the Spirit's living word to the present community. This understanding of Scripture as the Spirit's current address was characteristic of both the Qumran community (the pesher method treated ancient prophetic texts as addressing the community's immediate situation) and early Christianity (2 Tim 3:16: \"all Scripture is God-breathed and profitable\"; 1 Cor 10:11: \"these things happened to them as examples, and were written down for our instruction\"). The Spirit's testimony through Jeremiah is thus treated as addressed directly to the Hebrews community, not merely reported from the past.</p>",
    "16": "<p>\"This is the covenant I will make with them after those days\" reintroduces the Jeremiah 31:33 oracle (already cited in 8:10) but now as the culmination of the argument about Christ's completed sacrifice. The repetition of the Jeremiah citation reflects the Jewish homiletical practice of the <em>triasion</em> (triple citation) and the Seder-style recall of foundational texts at the argument's conclusion. Jeremiah's oracle was written during the final years of Jerusalem before the Babylonian destruction — a context of national catastrophe and covenant-failure. The promise of a new covenant was Jeremiah's answer to the demonstrated impossibility of the Sinai covenant maintaining itself through human faithfulness alone: God would act to ensure what the human partner had consistently failed to provide.</p>",
    "17": "<p>\"I will remember their sins no more\" is the ultimate promise of the Jeremiah oracle and functions as the theological conclusion of Hebrews' argument about sacrifice. In Jewish theology, divine remembrance was not merely cognitive but effective — when God \"remembered\" (zakar) Noah, Rachel, Hannah, the Exodus generation, the covenant people, it meant God acted on their behalf. Conversely, divine forgetting was not ignorance but active release: the prayers for forgiveness in the liturgy (Yom Kippur liturgy, the Psalms of repentance) consistently asked God not to remember sins against the petitioner. The promise that God will \"remember no more\" is therefore an eschatological speech-act: the divine record of sin is permanently cleared, not just temporarily covered.</p>",
    "18": "<p>\"Where there is forgiveness of these sins, there is no longer any offering for sin\" draws the practical conclusion from the Jeremiah oracle. In the Temple cult's logic, the need for ongoing sacrifice was tied to the ongoing accumulation of sin — as sin accumulated, offerings were required. The Yom Kippur ritual was the annual accounting and clearing; the daily tamid offering maintained the ongoing relationship; individual sin-offerings addressed specific transgressions. If forgiveness is final and complete, the entire system of accumulating-sin-and-responding-sacrifice is structurally unnecessary. Hebrews' conclusion is simple and devastating: the Jeremiah promise of complete forgiveness implies the obsolescence of the sacrificial system that sin's persistence had required.</p>",
    "20": "<p>\"The new and living way through the curtain, that is, through his flesh\" makes the temple curtain's tearing at the crucifixion theologically explicit. The great veil (paroket) of the Second Temple was described by Josephus (Jewish War 5.212-214) as a magnificent tapestry of Babylonian weaving depicting the heavens in blue, scarlet, and purple — a cosmic hanging representing the boundary between the human and divine spheres. The Mishnah (Shekalim 8:4-5) notes that it took 300 priests to handle the veil. Its tearing at the crucifixion in all three Synoptic Gospels was understood as a sign of the opened access to God. Hebrews makes this typological identification explicit: the curtain was Christ's flesh, and its tearing opened the \"new and living way\" — the crucified body as the opened door to God's presence.</p>",
    "21": "<p>\"A great high priest over the house of God\" recapitulates the fundamental claim of chapters 3-10 within the exhortation section. In the Second Temple period, the high priest was the most powerful religious figure in Jewish society — the Hasmonean high priests combined religious and political authority; the Herodian appointments were often political allies of the ruling family. The high priest's role at Yom Kippur as the sole mediator between Israel and God made the office theologically indispensable. For a Jewish-Christian community tempted to return to the synagogue and its Temple-focused religious life, the claim that they already have a \"great high priest\" is both pastoral reassurance and theological argument: they have what the Temple offers, and more.</p>",
    "22": "<p>\"Hearts sprinkled clean from an evil conscience and bodies washed with pure water\" uses the Day of Atonement blood-sprinkling (Lev 16:14-19) and purification-immersion imagery for Christian baptism. The high priest's multiple immersions on Yom Kippur (Mishnah Yoma 3:3) — five times during the day — purified him for the various stages of the ritual. The Levitical purity laws required immersion after various sources of impurity (Lev 11-15). The Qumran community's daily ritual immersions are described in the Rule of the Community (1QS 3:4-9) as the external sign of the internal purification that only comes through God's Spirit. Hebrews describes the community's baptism as the Christian counterpart: not the repeated ritual immersions of the Levitical system but the single, effective washing that corresponds to the once-for-all sprinkling with Christ's blood.</p>",
    "23": "<p>\"Hold firmly to the confession of our hope without wavering\" invokes the communal confession (<em>homologia</em>) that identified the Christian community publicly. In the Greco-Roman world, public confession of allegiance to a lord or god had significant social consequences: declaring \"Jesus is Lord\" rather than \"Caesar is Lord\" was a potentially dangerous public statement. The Jewish community similarly required formal confessions of faith (the Shema: Deut 6:4-9, recited twice daily) that constituted public identity. The Christian <em>homologia</em> was the equivalent public statement that marked the community's boundary and social identity. Holding it \"without wavering\" addressed the social pressure to recant or qualify the confession under persecution or community pressure.</p>",
    "24": "<p>\"Spur one another on to love and good works\" draws on the Jewish tradition of mutual accountability within the covenant community. The Qumran Rule of the Community (1QS 5:24-6:1) required members to rebuke one another in truth, humility, and brotherly love. The prophetic tradition of Leviticus 19:17 (\"You shall surely rebuke your neighbor\") was developed in Jewish ethics into a positive obligation of mutual moral correction — the responsibility to stimulate virtue in others was as real as the responsibility to avoid vice oneself. Hebrews' language of \"provoking\" or \"stimulating\" (<em>paroxysmos</em>) to love and good works uses the strongest possible word for this mutual-encouragement responsibility.</p>",
    "27": "<p>\"A terrifying expectation of judgment and a raging fire that will consume the adversaries\" draws on Isaiah 26:11 (\"Let the fire reserved for your enemies consume them\") and the fire-of-judgment tradition in the OT and Jewish apocalyptic. The wilderness narrative's \"consuming fire\" of God's holiness (Exod 24:17; Deut 4:24; 9:3) provided the foundational image. The Qumran War Scroll (1QM) describes the eschatological battle in which the fire of divine judgment destroys the children of darkness. 4 Ezra 7:36-38 describes the furnace of Gehenna as the eschatological judgment-fire for the wicked. Hebrews applies this judgment-fire language not to gentile enemies but to apostate insiders — the warning is to the community itself.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The death penalty for Mosaic law-rejection invoked here (\"anyone who rejected the law of Moses died without mercy on the testimony of two or three witnesses\") refers to Deuteronomy 17:6-7 (the death penalty for apostasy) and its application throughout the OT legal tradition. The Mishnah's tractate Sanhedrin devotes extensive attention to capital cases and the witness requirements. The Qumran community's Damascus Document describes expulsion from the community for serious violations — a community-level application of the Deuteronomic exclusion principle. Hebrews' use of the Deuteronomic capital punishment for apostasy as the baseline establishes the logical structure: if physical death without mercy was the penalty for rejecting the Mosaic covenant, the eschatological consequence of rejecting the new covenant is proportionally greater.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The threefold description — \"trampled the Son of God underfoot,\" \"treated as profane the blood of the covenant,\" \"insulted the Spirit of grace\" — invokes three spheres of Jewish sacrilege that together constitute total covenant apostasy. Trampling the Son is the language of utter contempt reserved for the destruction of things most sacred (Isa 63:6; Dan 8:10-13). Treating covenant blood as \"common\" (koinos) invokes the purity-system category of profanation — making holy what is set apart: Numbers 18:32 warned against profaning the holy gifts; Leviticus 10:10 required priests to distinguish between the holy and the common. Insulting the Spirit of grace uses the language of the sin against the Spirit (Matt 12:31-32) applied specifically to the post-conversion rejection of grace.</p>",
    "30": "<p>\"Vengeance is mine; I will repay\" and \"the Lord will judge his people\" are two citations from the Song of Moses (Deut 32:35-36). The Song of Moses was sung by Moses as a covenantal witness against Israel before his death (Deut 31:19-22) — its specific function was to testify against Israel's future apostasy. By citing the Song of Moses in the context of the apostasy warning, Hebrews activates the Song's own stated purpose: it was composed as a prophetic warning for exactly the situation of covenant violation that Hebrews addresses. The Song's judicial language — vengeance, repayment, judgment — places the apostasy question within the formal covenant-lawsuit structure that the prophets (Isaiah 1; Micah 6; Hosea 4) also employed.</p>",
    "31": "<p>\"It is a terrifying thing to fall into the hands of the living God\" (phoberon to empesein) inverts the OT comfort-formula. David's statement in 2 Samuel 24:14 (\"Let us fall into the hand of the LORD, for his mercy is great; but do not let me fall into human hands\") used \"falling into God's hands\" as the preferred mercy-option. Hebrews appropriates the same phrase but in the context of judgment rather than mercy: the \"living God\" (theos zōn) whose hands are a refuge for the trusting (Ps 31:5) is also the consuming fire (Heb 12:29; Deut 4:24) for those who spurn his covenant. The pastoral power of the inversion is significant — the audience knows the comfort-formula and feels its shock when reversed.</p>",
    "32": "<p>\"Recall the earlier days when, after you were enlightened, you endured a hard and painful struggle\" refers to the community's prior experience of persecution at their conversion. \"Enlightened\" (<em>phōtisthentes</em>) was an early Christian technical term for baptism — Justin Martyr (1 Apol. 61) uses <em>phōtismoi</em> for baptism explicitly, and the usage is already established by Hebrews. The word evoked the Jewish traditions of Torah as \"light\" (Ps 119:105; Prov 6:23; Bar 4:2) and the eschatological illumination of the end-time community (Isa 60:1-3; Dan 12:3). Entering the Christian community through baptism was a public act of \"enlightenment\" that immediately exposed the new believer to the social and legal consequences of having left their previous religious affiliation.</p>",
    "33": "<p>\"Sometimes being publicly exposed to reproach and affliction, and sometimes standing alongside those who were so treated\" describes the two modes of persecution: direct suffering and solidarity-suffering. The theatrical vocabulary (<em>theatrizomenoi</em> — made a public spectacle) reflects the Roman practice of public shaming and punishment in the arena or public spaces. Roman public life was organized around spectacle and public shame; being displayed as a prisoner, publicly accused, or publicly beaten was a mechanism of social control that worked through the honor-shame system. The community's solidarity with those publicly shamed — standing alongside the shamed rather than distancing oneself to protect one's own honor — was itself an act of counter-cultural witness that could expose the solidarity-person to the same shame.</p>",
    "34": "<p>\"You showed compassion to those in prison and joyfully accepted the plundering of your property\" describes concrete experiences of the persecuted community. Imprisonment for religious or political offenses was a common Roman practice; Paul, Peter, John the Baptist, and others in the NT narrative experienced it. Visiting the imprisoned was a recognized act of charity in both Jewish and Roman contexts: the obligation to care for prisoners appears in Matthew 25:36 and is reflected in practical community support described throughout Paul's letters. The \"plundering of property\" (harpagē tōn hyparchontōn) — forcible confiscation — was a consequence that Roman citizens and non-citizens faced when accused and convicted. The community's joyful acceptance of this loss reflected the eschatological revaluation of earthly possessions in light of \"a better possession that endures.\"</p>",
    "35": "<p>\"Do not throw away your confidence, which carries a great reward\" uses commercial and military vocabulary. <em>Parrēsia</em> (confidence, boldness) was the political right of free citizens to speak in the assembly without fear — it was a possession of the citizen class, not of slaves or foreigners. The command not to \"throw away\" (<em>apobalēte</em>) this confidence treats it as a valuable asset that can be discarded under pressure. <em>Misthapodosia</em> (reward, recompense) is the commercial term for wages paid for services rendered — the confidence carries a reward that makes it worth retaining even under pressure. The metaphor assumes that the community understands the cost-benefit calculation: short-term relief from social pressure versus long-term loss of the promised reward.</p>",
    "36": "<p>\"You need endurance, so that when you have done the will of God you may receive what was promised\" frames the current moment in the structure of promise-and-patience that characterized the patriarchal faith of chapter 11. The concept of divine promise requiring human endurance to receive was deeply embedded in Jewish covenantal theology: the Psalms of Ascent (Ps 120-134) celebrated the pilgrim's patient journey toward the Jerusalem festivals; the psalms of trust (Ps 27, 37, 46, 62) urged waiting for God. The Qumran community's commitment to patient endurance until the eschatological vindication appears throughout the Community Rule and the Hodayoth (Thanksgiving Hymns). The phrase \"having done the will of God\" echoes the Gethsemane tradition and the Son's own will-doing that the argument has developed throughout ch. 10.</p>",
    "37": "<p>The citation combines Isaiah 26:20 (\"Come, my people, enter your rooms and shut your doors behind you; hide yourselves for a little while until his wrath has passed by\") with Habakkuk 2:3 (\"For the revelation awaits an appointed time... Though it linger, wait for it; it will certainly come and will not delay\"). The Habakkuk text was central to Qumran's self-understanding: 1QpHab (the Habakkuk pesher) 7:5-14 interprets \"the vision still awaits an appointed time\" as referring to the delayed end that God would extend beyond what the prophets announced — the Qumran community waited through this extended delay. The LXX version of Habakkuk 2:3 introduces a personal subject (\"he will come\") where the Hebrew has a neuter (\"it will come\"), enabling the Christian application to Christ's parousia.</p>",
    "38": "<p>\"The righteous shall live by faith\" (Hab 2:4) was one of the most generative OT verses in the first-century Jewish and Christian world. Paul quotes it in Romans 1:17 and Galatians 3:11 as the hermeneutical key to the gospel. The Qumran Habakkuk pesher (1QpHab 8:1-3) interprets it as describing the community of those who observe the Torah and trust in the Teacher of Righteousness. Rabbi Simlai (in b. Makkot 24a, later) argued that Habakkuk reduced all 613 commandments to this single principle. Each community read \"faith\" (Heb. <em>emunah</em> = faithfulness/reliability) through its own lens: for Qumran, loyalty to the Teacher's interpretation; for Paul, trust in Christ; for Hebrews, the sustained trust-in-the-unseen that the faith-catalogue of ch. 11 will illustrate.</p>",
    "39": "<p>\"We do not belong to those who shrink back and are destroyed, but to those who have faith and preserve their souls\" echoes the communal self-definition of covenant groups who distinguished themselves from apostates. The Qumran Damascus Document (CD 1:3-4) describes those who had returned from the wilderness of the peoples as having \"defected\" — apostasy from the community was the gravest possible sin. The Matthean community defined itself against those who fell away (Matt 13:20-21; 24:10). Hebrews' pastoral self-definition — \"we are not of those who shrink back\" — is a collective encouragement that functions as a speech-act of communal identity: by saying it together, the community constitutes itself as the persevering group and not the shrinking group.</p>"
  },
  "11": {
    "2": "<p>\"The people of old received their commendation\" (<em>hoi presbyteroi</em> — the elders, ancestors) establishes the ancestral paradigm that will structure the entire faith-catalogue. Jewish culture gave enormous weight to the testimony of the ancestors: the rabbinic chain of tradition in Pirkei Avot 1:1 begins with Moses receiving Torah and passing it to Joshua, the elders, the prophets — each generation authenticated by the one before. Hebrews' claim that the ancestors were \"commended\" (<em>emarturēthēsan</em> — divinely witnessed-to, approved) through faith positions their scriptural commendation as a form of divine testimony that the current community inherits. The divine approval of the ancestors is not merely a historical record but a living tradition that speaks to the present generation.</p>",
    "3": "<p>\"By faith we understand that the universe was formed by God's command, so that what is seen was not made from visible things\" reflects the Jewish doctrine of <em>creatio ex nihilo</em> (creation from nothing). This doctrine, implicit in Genesis 1 and explicit in 2 Maccabees 7:28 (\"God made them out of nothing\"), was one of the defining features of Jewish monotheism against both Greek cosmology (which posited pre-existing matter) and Gnostic cosmologies (which distinguished the creator from the high God). Philo (On the Creation of the World 7-25) argues extensively for divine creation from nothing as the foundation of Jewish theology. The specific claim that the visible world was not made from \"visible things\" (phenomenōn) addresses the Platonic-Stoic assumption of pre-existing matter and ground the faith-as-evidence-of-unseen-things definition of v1 in the foundational invisible act of creation.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Enoch's translation without death (Gen 5:24: \"he was not, for God took him\") was one of the most developed biographical-theological expansions in Second Temple Judaism. The Enoch literature (1 Enoch, 2 Enoch, 3 Enoch) made Enoch the paradigmatic heavenly traveler and cosmic revealer — 1 Enoch 12-16 describes Enoch's heavenly journey; 2 Enoch describes his bodily transformation into an angelic being. The Book of Jubilees (4:21-23) describes Enoch's translation as a reward for his righteousness in an evil generation. Ben Sira 44:16 praises Enoch as a model of repentance. In this tradition, Enoch's translation became the supreme example of what faith-before-death could achieve — a bodily transport to the divine presence that anticipated the resurrection hope. Hebrews reads this against its tradition-background: Enoch was translated because he \"pleased God\" (LXX of Gen 5:24), and faith is the means of pleasing God (v6).</p>",
    "6": "<p>\"Without faith it is impossible to please God\" grounds the entire faith-catalogue in the principle that the Enoch tradition established: divine pleasure requires faith. The concept of \"pleasing God\" (<em>euarestēsai</em>) was central to the Hellenistic Jewish piety tradition: Ben Sira frequently counsels seeking to please God rather than humans; Psalms 19 and 119 describe the delight God takes in those who walk in Torah; Philo (On the Sacrifices of Abel and Cain 84) discusses divine pleasure as the goal of virtue. The claim that \"anyone who comes to him must believe that he exists and that he rewards those who earnestly seek him\" specifies the minimal faith-content required: not a theological system but a conviction about God's reality and moral governance. This minimal faith-base was shared between Judaism and early Christianity.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Noah's faith-response to divine warning drew on Genesis 6-9 and extensive Second Temple elaboration. The Wisdom of Solomon 14:6-7 describes Noah as the \"hope of the world\" who survived in a fragile vessel. Sirach 44:17-18 praises Noah as found perfect and righteous. Jubilees 5-10 expands the Noah narrative considerably. Philo (On Abraham 27-46) treats Noah as the embodiment of natural justice. 1 Peter 3:20-21 uses Noah's ark as a type of baptism. The community in which Hebrews circulated would likely know the Noah tradition in multiple forms. The specific elements Hebrews emphasizes — divine warning about unseen things, holy fear (<em>eulabeia</em>), the consequent building, and the implicit judgment on unbelieving contemporaries — reflect the faith-courage theme that will be developed throughout the chapter.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Abraham's departure from Ur of the Chaldees (Gen 12:1-9) was the paradigmatic act of faith-obedience in Jewish tradition. The Qumran Genesis Apocryphon (1QapGen) expands Abraham's journey with elaborate detail about his route and experiences. Jubilees 11-13 presents Abraham as the first monotheist who burned the family idols and left because of his conviction about the one God. Philo (On Abraham 60-88) develops Abraham's departure as the archetypal philosophical journey from the material to the spiritual. In Jewish homiletics, Abraham's departure was frequently compared to the soul's departure from earthly attachments. The phrase \"without knowing where he was going\" preserves the raw historical fact that the Journey of Faith precedes the knowledge of its destination — a principle directly applicable to the Hebrews community facing their own uncertain journey.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Abraham's tent-dwelling in the promised land as a \"stranger in a foreign country\" reflected a social-legal status that the first-century Jewish diaspora knew intimately. The term <em>paroikos</em> (sojourner, resident alien) designated those who lived in a place without full citizenship rights — they could own property (as Abraham purchased the cave of Machpelah, Gen 23) but had no political standing or legal protection equivalent to citizens. Jewish communities throughout the diaspora lived in exactly this status: recognized but not fully belonging, protected by local arrangements but not by right. The Hebrews community, whether in Rome or elsewhere, likely included members who literally were <em>paroikoi</em> in their city. The patriarchal model of tent-dwelling-in-promise resonated with their actual social condition.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Abraham's looking forward to \"the city with foundations, whose architect and builder is God\" introduces the heavenly city theme that will climax in 12:22 (\"You have come to Mount Zion... the city of the living God, the heavenly Jerusalem\") and 13:14 (\"we are looking for the city that is to come\"). The contrast between the tent (impermanent, portable, no foundation) and the city (permanent, foundationed, civic) reflects a fundamental ANE-Hellenistic distinction. In the ancient world, cities represented civilization, permanence, and ordered community — Aristotle (Politics 1252b) defined the city as the highest form of human association. Jewish apocalyptic tradition described the new Jerusalem as the eschatological city prepared in heaven and to be revealed at the end (4 Ezra 7:26; 10:27; Rev 3:12; 21:2). Abraham's tent-dwelling with eyes fixed on this heavenly city made him simultaneously a pilgrim and an eschatological citizen.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Sarah's capacity to conceive despite her age (Gen 17:17-19; 18:11-15; 21:1-7) was celebrated in Jewish tradition as one of the great miracles of the patriarchal period. The Talmud (b. Bava Metzia 87a) discusses the miraculous restoration of Sarah's youthful appearance. Genesis Rabbah 53:2-6 develops multiple midrashim on the miracle's nature. Ben Sira 25:25 (Hebrew text) mentions Sarah among the worthy women. Hebrews attributes the miracle to Sarah's faith in \"him who had made the promise\" — emphasizing the theological principle that the miracle required not just divine power but faith's reception. The <em>kata pistin</em> (by faith) applied to Sarah (despite her initial laughter at the promise, Gen 18:12) reflects Hebrews' generous reading of faith as the ultimate posture even when mixed with human doubt.</p>",
    "12": "<p>\"From this one man, and he as good as dead, came descendants as numerous as the stars in the sky and as countless as the sand on the seashore\" combines the two major covenant promises of Genesis (Gen 15:5: stars; Gen 22:17: stars and sand). The promise-fulfillment gap between Abraham's \"as good as dead\" condition and the astronomical/oceanic multitude of his descendants was a standard topic in Jewish reflection on divine faithfulness. The Passover Haggadah's recitation of the promise to Abraham and its fulfillment in the national Exodus (Deut 26:5-9) kept this promise-to-fulfillment narrative in constant liturgical memory. The rabbis developed the idea that God \"counts the stars and calls them by name\" (Ps 147:4) in connection with the Abraham promise — the stars are a perpetual sign of the covenant's ongoing validity.</p>",
    "14": "<p>\"People who say such things show that they are looking for a country of their own\" draws on the logic of public confession as revealing inner orientation. In the honor-shame culture of the ancient world, what one publicly acknowledged — through one's words, associations, religious practices, and community affiliations — constituted one's social identity. The patriarchs' public self-identification as strangers and sojourners was a social statement as well as a theological one: they were declaring their primary allegiance to a community and a homeland not visible in the present order. For the Hebrews community facing pressure to assimilate into Roman-Jewish social norms, the patriarchal model offered a principled framework: their social nonconformity was not failure or weakness but the proper posture of those whose citizenship is in the heavenly polis.</p>",
    "15": "<p>\"If they had been thinking of the country they had left, they would have had opportunity to return\" reflects the actual experience of immigrant and diaspora communities. Archaeological and literary evidence shows that diaspora Jews who moved to new cities maintained connections with their places of origin for generations; return migration was common. The Jewish diaspora communities in Alexandria, Rome, Babylon, and elsewhere maintained identity-links to Jerusalem through Temple taxes, pilgrimage, and correspondence. The argument from opportunity is therefore not merely logical but reflects the real social options available to those who leave their homeland: they could return if that homeland were their primary loyalty. The patriarchs' non-return from Canaan to Mesopotamia revealed that their homeland was not Mesopotamia but somewhere they had not yet reached.</p>",
    "16": "<p>\"God is not ashamed to be called their God, for he has prepared a city for them\" reflects a profound inversion of the honor-shame dynamic. In the Greco-Roman patron-client world, the patron who acknowledged lowly clients in public was extending significant social capital to them. The gods of Greek and Roman religion were associated with powerful, prosperous, successful cities and peoples — divine identity was tied to the honor of those who worshipped the deity. YHWH's willingness to be identified as the God of wandering, tent-dwelling, stateless sojourners ran directly against this logic. The divine willingness to be publicly associated with the socially marginal — embodied in the promise to be Abraham's God (Gen 17:7) and Israel's God when Israel was a slave people in Egypt — was itself a theological claim about the character of the God of Israel.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The Aqedah (binding of Isaac, Gen 22:1-19) was the most theologically dense narrative in the Jewish tradition, generating more interpretive attention than any other patriarchal story. The Mishnah (Avot 5:3) lists the Aqedah as the tenth and greatest of Abraham's ten trials. Jubilees 17-18 attributes the Aqedah to Mastema's (Satan's) suggestion — parallel to the Job narrative. The Targum Pseudo-Jonathan of Genesis 22 gives Isaac an active, willing role in his own binding (prefiguring his age as 26-37 years, not a child). The liturgy of Rosh Hashanah and Yom Kippur invokes the merit of the Aqedah (zekhut avot) as a basis for divine mercy on Israel. Hebrews' reading of the Aqedah as a faith-act that prefigured resurrection participates in this rich tradition while directing it toward the specific claim about Jesus's death and resurrection.</p>",
    "18": "<p>\"It is through Isaac that your offspring will be reckoned\" (Gen 21:12) was a crucial text in rabbinic discussion of Gentile inclusion in Israel. Paul quotes the same verse in Romans 9:7 to argue that physical descent from Abraham does not automatically confer covenant standing — \"in Isaac shall your offspring be named\" means the election is particular, not automatic. Hebrews uses the verse differently: to heighten the paradox of the Aqedah. If God had specified that the covenant line would run through Isaac, the command to sacrifice Isaac was a direct apparent contradiction of the promise. Abraham's faith was therefore not simple compliance with a command but a theologically reasoned act of trust that God could resolve the contradiction — even through resurrection.</p>",
    "19": "<p>\"Abraham reasoned that God could even raise the dead, and so in a manner of speaking he did receive Isaac back from death\" makes explicit a midrashic reading of Genesis 22 that was developed in Jewish tradition. Midrash Genesis Rabbah 56:4 discusses whether God's promise could be fulfilled after Isaac's death; the Binding of Isaac came to be understood as a proleptic sacrifice — Isaac symbolically dying and returning. The Targum Neofiti (Gen 22:10) describes the angels of service appearing and weeping as Abraham raised the knife. The explicit resurrection interpretation in Hebrews («en parabolē» — \"as a parable/type\") positioned Isaac's near-death-and-return as the paradigmatic type of resurrection, making the argument from Abraham's faith simultaneously an argument about resurrection as the mechanism of promise-fulfillment.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Isaac's deathbed blessing of Jacob and Esau (Gen 27-28) was a theologically significant act in Jewish tradition: the patriarchal blessing was understood as effective speech that transferred divine favor and destiny. The fact that Isaac blessed Jacob believing him to be Esau (Gen 27:18-29), and that the blessing could not be retracted when the deception was discovered (Gen 27:33-40), established the irrevocability of patriarchal blessing in Jewish legal theology. The Mishnah (Bava Batra 7:1) discusses the legal force of deathbed declarations. Hebrews' brief reference to Isaac blessing \"in regard to their future\" emphasizes the forward-looking faith-dimension: Isaac spoke of things he could not see, trusting that the words he spoke would shape a future beyond his own death.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Jacob's deathbed blessing of Joseph's two sons (Gen 48) and his crossing of his hands to give the greater blessing to Ephraim (the younger) over Manasseh (the older) was a pattern repeated in the patriarchal narratives (Jacob himself had received the elder's blessing over Esau). The deliberate reversal of birth-order in divine election was a recurring theme: Abel over Cain, Isaac over Ishmael, Jacob over Esau, Ephraim over Manasseh, David over his elder brothers. The tradition of the younger's election over the elder (reflecting divine sovereign choice rather than human custom) was a theological motif that Paul develops extensively in Romans 9:6-13. Jacob's worship at the head of his staff (from LXX of Gen 47:31) was the posture of reverence in weakness — dying but still worshipping, the posture of faith sustained to the last moment of life.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Joseph's dying instruction about his bones (Gen 50:24-25) was a faith-act that both demonstrated and communicated a conviction about Israel's future destiny. Exodus 13:19 records that Moses took Joseph's bones from Egypt — the fulfillment of the oath that Joseph made his brothers swear in Genesis 50:25. Joshua 24:32 records the burial of Joseph's bones in Shechem after the Canaan conquest. The bones thus made a journey spanning four generations (Joseph to Joshua), their presence in the exodus caravan a physical testimony that Joseph's faith in the Exodus promise outlasted his death. Hebrews' brief reference to this tradition assumes the audience knows the full narrative — the bones as a multi-generational faith-artifact connecting the patriarchal promise to the Mosaic fulfillment.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Moses' parents (Amram and Jochebed, Exod 6:20; Num 26:59) hiding him three months (Exod 2:2-3) was elaborated in Jewish tradition. Josephus (Antiquities 2.210-217) describes Amram receiving a divine dream about Moses' future greatness before his birth. The Targum Pseudo-Jonathan on Exodus 2:2 elaborates Jochebed's perception of Moses' extraordinary quality. Acts 7:20 describes Moses as \"beautiful before God\" (asteios tō theō). In the Hellenistic world, the birth of an unusually beautiful child was interpreted as a divine sign — Hebrews' note that the parents \"saw that he was a fine child\" reflects this convention of the divinely-marked infant. Their civil disobedience against Pharaoh's edict (Exod 1:22: every Hebrew boy to be cast into the Nile) placed them in the tradition of the Hebrew midwives (Exod 1:15-21) who feared God more than the royal command.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Moses' refusal to be known as \"the son of Pharaoh's daughter\" meant renouncing a social identity of extraordinary privilege. Egyptian royal adoption conferred rank, resources, and a future of leadership within the most powerful empire of the ancient world. The tradition that Moses was educated in all Egyptian wisdom (Acts 7:22: \"Moses was educated in all the wisdom of the Egyptians and was powerful in speech and action\") — elaborated extensively by Josephus (Antiquities 2.238-253), who describes Moses's military leadership of an Egyptian campaign — makes the refusal of this identity all the more remarkable. Philo (On the Life of Moses 1.9-16) describes Moses's royal education in detail before his identification with the Hebrew slaves. The honor-shame calculus: Moses deliberately chose the lower social identity over the higher one, reversing every conventional calculation of self-interest.</p>",
    "25": "<p>\"The fleeting pleasures of sin\" uses Hellenistic vocabulary for the Epicurean evaluation of pleasure as the supreme good. Epicurus taught that pleasure (specifically, the absence of pain and anxiety) was the highest goal of human life; his school's motto was said to be \"pleasure is the beginning and end of the blessed life\" (Letter to Menoeceus 128). Hebrews' phrase <em>proskairon</em> (temporary, for-a-time) directly addresses the Epicurean calculation: even if sin's pleasures are genuine pleasures, they are temporary (<em>pros kairon</em>) — bounded by time and therefore of limited value. The contrast with the \"greater wealth\" of suffering for the Messiah uses the same economic-calculation language: Moses performed a deliberate cost-benefit analysis and chose the option with greater long-term value.</p>",
    "26": "<p>\"The reproach of Christ\" applied to Moses' experience is a typological identification of Moses' suffering with the Messiah's suffering — Moses bore reproach as a representative of God's covenant people in a way that structurally anticipated Christ's bearing of reproach. Psalm 89:50-51 (\"Remember, Lord, how your servant has been mocked... how your enemies, LORD, have mocked, how they have mocked every step of your anointed one\") connects the suffering of God's servant with the suffering of the anointed king. Hebrews reads Moses' willingness to bear Egypt's contempt as participation in the pattern of the righteous sufferer that finds its ultimate expression in Christ. The phrase also implies that the community's current reproach (10:33) participates in the same tradition — they share Moses' and ultimately Christ's reproach.</p>",
    "27": "<p>\"He persevered because he saw him who is invisible\" describes the inner-vision that enabled Moses' sustained endurance. Jewish tradition celebrated Moses' unique access to divine vision: Exodus 33:11 (\"the LORD would speak to Moses face to face, as one speaks to a friend\") and Numbers 12:8 (\"with him I speak face to face, clearly and not in riddles; he sees the form of the LORD\") established Moses as the prophet who had seen what no other could see. Philo (On the Life of Moses 1.158-162) describes Moses' mystical vision of God. The Mekhilta on Exodus 14:13-14 describes Israel at the Red Sea as those who could not yet see what Moses saw. Hebrews applies the \"seeing-the-invisible\" motif to Moses' ordinary daily endurance: the vision of God that sustained Israel's supreme prophet is the same faith-vision available to the current community.</p>",
    "28": "<p>\"He kept the Passover and the application of blood, so that the destroyer of the firstborn would not touch them\" draws on Exodus 12:1-28 and the extensive Passover tradition. The Passover Seder (the annual commemorative meal retelling the Exodus) was the central family-liturgical observance of Jewish life, rehearsing the Exodus narrative in each generation as a present-tense re-experience (Mishnah Pesahim 10:5: \"In every generation a person is obligated to see himself as if he personally left Egypt\"). The application of hyssop-dipped blood to the doorposts (Exod 12:22) was the protective act whose efficacy depended on faith-obedience to the divine command. The \"destroyer\" (<em>olothreuōn</em>) was identified in later tradition with the angel of death (Exod 12:23; 1 Cor 10:10) — a personification of the death-power that the Passover blood averted.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The Reed Sea crossing (Exod 14) was the foundational liberation event of Israel's history, commemorated in the annual Passover and in the Song of the Sea (Exod 15). The event was recalled throughout the OT as the paradigm of divine salvation (Ps 77:16-20; 106:9-12; Isa 51:10; 63:11-13). Second Temple Judaism developed the crossing extensively: Jubilees 48-49 presents it as part of the cosmic battle between God and Mastema (Satan); Wisdom 10:17-18 attributes the crossing to divine Wisdom. The Jewish midrash developed the tradition that the Israelites walked on dry sea-bottom while seeing fish through crystal walls of water (Mekhilta Beshallah). The Egyptians' drowning in the same water that was dry land for Israel was the definitive demonstration that the same divine act could be deliverance for some and judgment for others.</p>",
    "30": "<p>The fall of Jericho's walls (Josh 6) after the Israelites marched around them for seven days was among the most celebrated military miracles in Jewish tradition. Joshua's campaign in Canaan was understood as the continuation of the Exodus deliverance — the same divine power that parted the Reed Sea brought down the walls of the first Canaanite fortress. The marching protocol (seven days, seven priests with shofars, seven circuits on the seventh day, a great shout) made the military action explicitly liturgical — the battle was won by worship before the weapons were deployed. Jewish tradition (Mishnah Rosh Hashanah 3:8) connected the shofar of Jericho with the shofar-blowing liturgy of the holidays, embedding the military-liturgical miracle in ongoing religious practice.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Rahab's inclusion in the faith-heroes catalogue was remarkable given her profession. The Midrash developed Rahab's story extensively: she was reputed to be so beautiful that merely hearing her name could provoke lustful thoughts (b. Megillah 15a). Ruth Rabbah 2:1 lists Rahab among the four most beautiful women of the world. Despite this, her faith-act in hiding the spies (Josh 2) and her red-cord signal (Josh 2:18-21) became the basis for her inclusion in the covenant community. Matthew 1:5 places Rahab in the genealogy of Jesus. The Mishnah (Sifre on Numbers 78) notes that Rahab was one of several proselytes who achieved great standing in Israel. Her inclusion by Hebrews alongside the patriarchs and Moses as a faith-example deliberately crosses social and ethnic boundaries — faith, not lineage, is the qualification.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The list of judges and kings — Gideon, Barak, Samson, Jephthah, David, Samuel — represents the period of Israel's Judges and early monarchy, a period characterized by repeated cycles of apostasy, oppression, and deliverance (the Deuteronomic cycle of Judges). These figures were celebrated in Jewish tradition despite their significant moral failures: Samson's relationships with foreign women, Gideon's ephod, Jephthah's vow. Josephus (Antiquities books 5-6) retells their stories apologetically for Greco-Roman audiences. 1 Maccabees 2:51-60 uses a similar list of ancestral heroes (though with different members) to encourage the Maccabean fighters. The rhetorical device of the incomplete list — \"time would fail me to tell of\" — creates the impression of an inexhaustible treasury of faith-examples beyond those already cited.</p>",
    "33": "<p>\"Who through faith conquered kingdoms, enforced justice, obtained promises, stopped the mouths of lions\" summarizes the achievements of the judges, prophets, and martyrs. \"Conquered kingdoms\" — Joshua, Judges, David, the Maccabees. \"Enforced justice\" — Samuel, Elijah, the prophets. \"Obtained promises\" — those who received specific divine promises fulfilled in their lifetimes (Caleb: Josh 14:9-14; David: 2 Sam 7). \"Stopped the mouths of lions\" — Samson (Judg 14:6), David (1 Sam 17:34-36), Daniel (Dan 6). The Daniel reference was particularly significant: the Danielic lion-pit narrative was a model of faith-under-state-pressure that the Hebrews community facing Roman persecution could directly apply to their situation. 1 Maccabees 2:60 includes Daniel in the same catalogue of ancestral heroes.</p>",
    "34": "<p>\"Quenched the fury of the flames\" — the three Hebrew youth in the fiery furnace (Dan 3) — was among the most celebrated miracles of the Second Temple period. The image of the fourth figure in the fire (Dan 3:25, described as \"like a son of God\") was interpreted christologically by early Christians and as the angel Michael by Jewish interpreters. The three youth's refusal to bow to Nebuchadnezzar's image became a paradigm for Jewish martyrdom and resistance under foreign pressure: 1 Maccabees 2:59 cites them as examples for the Maccabean revolt. The Daniel martyrdom stories (Dan 3 and 6) were particularly relevant for a community facing pressure to conform to foreign religious demands — their \"weakness turned to strength\" was the archetypal faith-under-persecution narrative.</p>",
    "35": "<p>\"Women received their dead, raised to life again\" refers to the resurrections performed through Elijah (1 Kgs 17:17-24: the widow of Zarephath's son) and Elisha (2 Kgs 4:32-37: the Shunammite woman's son). These stories were celebrated as evidence of prophetic power and divine compassion. The second half of the verse — \"there were others who were tortured, refusing to accept release, so that they might rise again to a better resurrection\" — refers specifically to the Maccabean martyrs of 2 Maccabees 6-7. The mother and seven sons who were tortured one by one under Antiochus IV Epiphanes (167 BCE), each declaring faith in the resurrection (2 Macc 7:9, 11, 14, 23, 29), provided the paradigmatic example of faith-unto-death for a better resurrection. 4 Maccabees 5-18 retells the same story with elaborate philosophical development of how reason (piety) overcomes pain.</p>",
    "36": "<p>\"Some faced jeers and flogging, and even chains and imprisonment\" describes the lower-level persecution that fell short of martyrdom but constituted real suffering. The Jewish prophetic tradition included numerous examples of imprisonment and flogging for faithfulness: Jeremiah was beaten and placed in stocks (Jer 20:2) and thrown into a cistern (Jer 38:6); Micaiah was imprisoned by Ahab (1 Kgs 22:27); John the Baptist was imprisoned by Herod Antipas (Matt 14:3). The early Christian community continued this tradition: Peter and John were imprisoned (Acts 4:3); Paul repeatedly described his imprisonment and beatings (2 Cor 11:23-27; Phil 1:13-14). These less dramatic but pervasive forms of suffering for faith formed the everyday experience of the community Hebrews addressed.</p>",
    "39": "<p>\"All these, though commended through their faith, did not receive what had been promised\" introduces the theology of eschatological deferral that structures the entire faith-catalogue. In Jewish tradition, the question of when the righteous dead would receive their promised reward was a live theological question. 4 Ezra 7:88-101 describes the seven stages through which righteous souls wait after death; 2 Baruch 30:1-5 describes the resurrection of the righteous when the Messiah returns. The Mishnah (Sanhedrin 10:1) affirms that all Israel has a share in the world to come. Hebrews' claim that the OT saints received commendation but not the complete promised inheritance sets up the community's role as the generation in which the promise is fulfilled — not a disparagement of the ancestors but a claim about the corporate and eschatological character of the promised salvation.</p>",
    "40": "<p>\"God had planned something better for us so that only together with us would they be made perfect\" articulates the corporate and eschatological dimension of salvation that was characteristic of Jewish apocalyptic thought. Jewish eschatology was community-oriented: the promised resurrection and restoration applied to Israel as a people, not merely to individuals. The Mishnah's \"all Israel has a share in the world to come\" was a corporate claim. 4 Ezra 7:26-44 describes the messianic banquet in which the righteous of all ages will participate together. Hebrews' claim that the OT saints cannot be perfected without the NT community is a claim about the unity of the one people of God across both testaments — the OT saints' faith pointed forward to something they could not receive until the Christological fulfillment was accomplished and its community completed.</p>"
  }
}
""")

def main():
    existing = load_comm("mkt-context", "hebrews")
    merge_comm(existing, HEBREWS)
    save_comm("mkt-context", "hebrews", existing)
    total = sum(len(v) for v in existing.values())
    print(f"Hebrews 10-11 mkt-context gaps filled: {len(existing)} chapters, {total} verses written.")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
